liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: It's all got to do with the falling price of iron ore futures. They've taken a hit in response to weaker-than-expected steel consumption, completion of pre-holiday restocking and possible output restrictions. On the Singapore Exchange, benchmark October iron ore was 3.2% lower at $117.25 a tonne. Several factors have jointly contributed to the broad weakness in raw materials, said Pei Hao, a Shanghai-based analyst at international brokerage firm FIS. "It becomes increasingly clear that demand has hit the ceiling amid weaker-than-expected steel sales for September and October, and after the replenishment of raw materials to meet production needs over the upcoming week-long holiday break came to an end," he said. Weighing on prices of the key steelmaking ingredient are also "concerns of tighter monetary policy", analysts at ANZ bank said in a note. â€” with Reuters

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The federal opposition has described the employment white paper as a "missed opportunity". The government has outlined measures it plans to introduce to ensure Australians have the skills they need for future jobs, and incentives to keep people working. It includes allowing pensioners and veterans to work more hours before their pension is reduced and accelerating the take up of higher apprenticeships in priority areas. Shadow Treasurer Angus Taylor says while some proposals have merit, he's concerned about other government plans. "We do see this white paper as missed opportunity," he said. "We see IR reforms coming forward from this government that business has universally condemned. "They are the wrong initiatives for the time. If we are to knock down those barriers to work we need to make sure we have the right IR policies in place."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: White Paper 'a missed opportunity', Coalition says

children.content: The federal opposition has described the employment white paper as a "missed opportunity".
The government has outlined measures it plans to introduce to ensure Australians have the skills they need for future jobs, and incentives to keep people working.
It includes allowing pensioners and veterans to work more hours before their pension is reduced and accelerating the take up of higher apprenticeships in priority areas.
Shadow Treasurer Angus Taylor says while some proposals have merit, he's concerned about other government plans.
"We do see this white paper as missed opportunity," he said.
"We see IR reforms coming forward from this government that business has universally condemned.
"They are the wrong initiatives for the time. If we are to knock down those barriers to work we need to make sure we have the right IR policies in place."
